    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-03T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-03T07:00:00-05:00" n="265"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d265">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">874.00/8–345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barnes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-03T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 3, 1945—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 3:33 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>410. Reference my telegram 403, July 31.<note n="18" xml:id="d265fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1945Berlinv02#pg_734">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 734</ref>.</note> The Fatherland Front
                    has now launched general campaign for invalidation of candidatures on opposition
                    list. Some are held ineligible on grounds that they are members of FF parties,
                    such as Nikola Petkov, or failed to resign government positions within allotted
                    time, as Peter Koev, Agrarian Secretary General of Ministry of Finance, or
                    others are charged with being supporters of G. M. Dimitrov, even of Alexander
                        Tsankov,<note n="19" xml:id="d265fn2">Bulgarian Prime Minister after <hi
                            rend="italic">coup d’état</hi>, June 1923; convicted <hi rend="italic"
                            >in absentia</hi> as war criminal.</note> or collaborators with pre-FF
                    governments, anti-Semitic or simply Fascists. Three latter charges are utterly
                    ridiculous when examined in light of fact that most candidates in question
                    played leading role <pb facs="0286" n="274" xml:id="pg_274"/> in public affairs
                    from Sept 9 until very recently. Intimidation by widespread arrests in the
                    provinces even beatings authentically reported.</p>
                <p>Repeated Moscow as 211.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Barnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
